## 3. Pairwise correlations on the 15 1-x_term probes

Selected entries from the full correlation matrix (`correlation_matrix_1_x_term`):

| Pair | Pearson r | Interpretation |
|---|---|---|
| `ulp_spread_log2` × `E_log2_base_operand` | **−0.6431** | Moderate negative. **The two are NOT redundant** — they capture different substrate aspects. Both remain in the basis. |
| `ulp_spread_log2` × `base_operand` | −0.2044 | Weak. ulp_spread isn't a simple function of base_operand. |
| `E_log2_base_operand` × `base_operand` | +0.8356 | Strong (monotone log relation). Confirms E-family collapse to E representative. |
| `ulp_spread_log2` × `min_ulp` | −0.8582 | Strong. Within the BACL family — same equivalence group, ulp_spread_log2 is the representative. |
| `ulp_spread_log2` × `max_ulp` | (undefined — `max_ulp` constant in this probe set) | max_ulp has zero variance — preconditional flag, not a basis element. |
| `E_log2_base_operand` × `in_sterbenz_cluster` | (deterministic) | Boolean interval test on E. Equivalence collapse. |
| `conjecture_c_in_normal_range` × `c2_lattice_chain_applies` | (constant True both) | Joint precondition. Demoted. |

Full matrix in `phase_c_irreducible_basis.json` `correlation_matrix_1_x_term`.

The pivotal correlation is **ulp_spread_log2 × E ≈ −0.64**. Tight enough to share some binade structure (both observables read the operand chain's binade arrangement), loose enough that **they carry independent information**. If this had been ≥ |0.95|, one of the two would have been demoted; if it had been ≈ 0, they'd be fully orthogonal. The middle ground confirms: keep both, and Phase D's transformation-invariance audit will determine which is the more fundamental substrate quantity.

