## 6. Implications for the substrate invariant `I(F, x)`

The campaign authority's invariant `I(F, x)` must be built from substrate primitives. Phase C's basis identifies three substrate-derived ingredients:

- **`ulp_spread_log2`**: operand-chain binade-structure observable. Sensitive to which operands matter at the probe point.
- **`E_log2_base_operand`**: endpoint-distance substrate image. Sensitive to proximity to singular boundaries (Sterbenz cluster, lightspeed, horizon).
- **`two_form_partition`**: algebraic-form structural invariant. Sensitive to which routes produce silent vs residual_carrying behaviour.

These are the three orthogonal substrate axes the synthesis target must combine. Plus Phase E's V4-native K_G as the missing canonical-curvature ingredient (added under plan-mode discipline).

The substrate-as-probe instrument therefore has **4 substrate axes**: BACL spectrum (substrate granularity), E (substrate distance), partition (substrate algebraic-route structure), K_G (substrate curvature). All P1-satisfied, all substrate-derived, none requiring iteration on F.

That's the synthesis target Phase F will work with.

